HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World) constructs a multi-layer proximity graph. Each node connects to its M nearest neighbours. Queries traverse graph edges from an entry point, navigating toward the query vector. HNSW achieves higher recall at lower latency than IVFFlat on most workloads and supports incremental inserts without retraining. Trade-offs: HNSW uses more memory (roughly M × 8–16 bytes per vector) and has slower build time.

